Dhugal Forgefyre <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=aradil>Aradil</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/15/02 7:26:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=229.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: On Justification</span><hr size=1> Okay, one last thing from me in response to Kimaya and then I'll shut up and let other people talk <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
(The following is drawn from my own non-EQ RPing experiences. Take it as you will.)<br>
<br>
Say my friend gets a million dollars, totally randomly. I would (hopefully) not be jealous and would be very happy for him. His life is a lot better now, and life for everyone moves on.<br>
<br>
Now, say you're playing a (random example) LARP with this same friend and a bunch of other people. The Storyteller gives your friend some totally overpowering item or ability, and makes up some brief story of how he gets it (&quot;A long lost relative died and left you this magic amulet. Enjoy.&quot;). Would you be just as happy for him? Maybe, in a way, but both you and he (and ESPECIALLY everyone else) realize how much this is going to change the dynamics of the game. The game has suddenly become less fun for everyone else because one person has gotten some kind of help that doesn't really follow from the rest of the storyline. People might feel that all their efforts are stupid when the big rewards are handed out essentially at random, as they perceive it. Many people, sometimes good RPers who are assets to the game, will say &quot;WTF, that's BS&quot; and won't play anymore. The rest of the game has changed for everyone else who remains because now all of a sudden there is this stupid magic amulet that this one player has, and everyone has to rearrange their storyline.<br>
<br>
The key here is that RP, for it to stay RP, has to be more &quot;realistic&quot; in some ways than RL, or it's not fun. Almost all of the game rulebooks (and my own gaming experiences) I've read stress over and over (for storytellers) that you MUST be fair and equitable to your players or the game will be ruined for everyone. <br>
<br>
In the above situation, eventually you end up with no RPers (because they've all left) and a Storyteller who is handing out magic amulets like candy because all the players who stay whine for one (or they leave).<br>
<br>
If player XXX on the other side of the world gets a magic amulet (e.g. Uber_gear_01), will that affect me? Probably not, since I might never see that person. But if a bunch of people start getting amulets, well, then it does affect me. And I've played on the uber servers before, and, well, I came to FV in part to get away from that, and I know many other RPers here feel the same way. If all the RPers leave, where does that leave RP on FV?<br>
<br>
EDIT: The issue isn't about twinking so much, per se, because it seems perfectly valid for an older player to pass along items to a newer player when the older player is done with them, or something similar. It's just, some part of me says that more twinking is going to lead to a rise in the number of &quot;d00d&quot; people who don't RP, followed by a decrease in the number of people who make this server fun. I'm probably, hopefully wrong <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=aradil>Aradil</A> at: 1/15/02 10:45:23 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ugrimwyrd.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Grimwyrd</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 87<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/15/02 8:35:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=229.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: On Justification</span><hr size=1> I guess I'm lucky. I don't see the problem here on Firoina Vie. Every one of the &quot;ubers&quot; I've bumped into were very nice and they roleplayed (or, at least, failed to speak dude-speak at me).<br>
<br>
Let's see. One of the most &quot;uber&quot; people I've met would have to be Restoria (congrats again on the epic, milady). I bumped into her in the Freeport bank, and we briefly discussed the fact that we both served Karana (her as a cleric and I as a druid). We spoke in character for a bit, and she ended up giving me a couple knick-knacks from her overflowing bank. It was very kind of her and completely &quot;in character&quot;.<br>
<br>
Another &quot;uber&quot; sort I've met briefly was Auno. I saw him at the Freeport Fishing Tournament (which he won, congrats again Master Fisher). Not many &quot;ubers&quot; on other servers would master fishing or bother to go to a fishing event, but that's the kind of thing that is great about FV.<br>
<br>
I could go on and on. The bottom line is that most people who are already 50+ on this server have completely respected my desire to roleplay, no matter how &quot;uber&quot; they are.<br>
<br>
On the occasions when people say things like &quot;what class r u?&quot; I usually respond &quot;I serve Karana, the Storm Lord, as one of His druids&quot;. This lets people know that I am not interested in conversing in dude-speak, and most people pick up on that right away. They either start speaking in-character themselves, or just leave me alone.<br>
<br>
In fact, the only people over the last several weeks that have &quot;disrespected&quot; my roleplaying experience have been dudes in the 5th-20th level range who simply just don't get it.<br>
<br>
